04815nam a22005415i 9780226815794DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021034811  a97802268157947 a10.7208/chicago/97802268157942doi  a(DE-B1597)590431  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPR461b.B73 2022 4aPR461 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a823/.8091 aBrilmyer, S. Pearl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Science of Character :bHuman Objecthood and the Ends of Victorian Realism /cS. Pearl Brilmyer. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b5 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThinking Literature00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of figures -- tIntroduction. Ethology, or the Science of Character -- tChapter 1. Plasticity, Form, and the Physics of Character in Eliot’s Middlemarch -- tChapter 2. Sensing Character in Impressions of Theophrastus Such -- tChapter 3. The Racialization of Surface in Hardy’s Sketch of Temperament and Hereditary Science -- tChapter 4. Schopenhauer and the Determination of Women’s Character -- tChapter 5. The Intimate Pulse of Reality; or, Schreiner’s Ethological Realism -- tCoda. Spontaneous Generations of Character between Realism and Modernism -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Science of Character makes a bold new claim for the power of the literary by showing how Victorian novelists used fiction to theorize how character forms. In 1843, the Victorian philosopher John Stuart Mill called for the establishment of a new science, “the science of the formation of character.” Although Mill’s proposal failed as scientific practice, S. Pearl Brilmyer maintains that it found its true home in realist fiction of the period, which employed the literary figure of character to investigate the nature of embodied experience. Bringing to life Mill’s unrealized dream of a science of character, novelists such as George Eliot, Thomas Hardy, and Olive Schreiner turned to narrative to explore how traits and behaviors in organisms emerge and develop, and how aesthetic features—shapes, colors, and gestures—come to take on cultural meaning through certain categories, such as race and sex. Engaged with materialist science and philosophy, these authors transformed character from the liberal notion of the inner truth of an individual into a materially determined figuration produced through shifts in the boundaries between the body’s inside and outside. In their hands, Brilmyer argues, literature became a science, not in the sense that its claims were falsifiable or even systematically articulated, but in its commitment to uncovering, through a fictional staging of realistic events, the laws governing physical and affective life. The Science of Character redraws late Victorian literary history to show how women and feminist novelists pushed realism to its aesthetic and philosophical limits in the crucial span between 1870 and 1920.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPersonality development. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  ajohn stuart mill, science, character, identity, realist fiction, embodiment, olive schreiner, thomas hardy, george eliot, literature, victorian, england, race, gender, aesthetics, affect, emotions, nonfiction, middlemarch, temperament, heredity, schopenhauer, femininity, women, feminism, nature, modernism, humanity, honor, materialism, theophrastus such.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Comp